        "text": "The data-mining of Quentin Van Doosselaere (2006) will suggest how, over two centuries, a capitalist trade economy spun out in networks around medieval Genoa. And closer to home, on a smaller scale, we’ll watch Andrew Abbott (1999) tease out (as analyst, as observer, and also as participant) how a department and discipline emerged, in decades of orientings and dealings and commitments, as a robust cloud of common sensibility—the “style” discussed in chapter 4around a scholarly journal nested in the University of Chicago. Other studies and observation suggest that similar portrayals and themes can also apply for much smaller scopes in sociocultural time and space.1 Altogether, chapters 1–6 offer six distinct viewpoints (or takes or humors or framings) on sociocultural process. Metaphorically, these are “takes” on us as schools of fish in a vast river, with tributaries and shoals and yet also some great depths."
